<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-31_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-32_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-33_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions
</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-btwLGw cuLvxI pf-35_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-36_ pf-text-1"><strong>Epistaxis </strong>- Medical term for nosebleeds.














</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-38_ pf-text-1"><strong>Anterior nosebleed</strong> - This occurs at the front of the nose and constitutes 90% of cases. It is usually less severe.














</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-40_ pf-text-1"><strong>Posterior nosebleed</strong> - Less common, occurring deep within the nose and often requiring medical attention.














</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-42_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-43_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-44_ pf-heading-1-h3">Relevant legislation and regulations
</h3><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-46_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>In the UK, first aid for children in educational and care settings is governed by several pieces of legislation and guidelines:


<br>
</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-btwLGw cuLvxI pf-48_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-49_ pf-text-1"><strong>Health and Safety (First-Aid) Regulations 1981</strong> - Requires employers to provide adequate and appropriate equipment, facilities, and personnel to ensure employees receive immediate attention if they are injured or taken ill at work.















</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-51_ pf-text-1"><strong>Early Years Foundation Stage (EYFS)</strong> - Stipulates that all early years providers must have a paediatric first-aider available on the premises at all times children are present.















</li></ul><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-53_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Training providers, like The Mandatory Training Group, offer courses that ensure compliance with these regulations, enhancing safety and preparedness in child-centred environments.



<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-55_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-56_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-57_ pf-heading-1-h3">Best practices for treating nosebleeds in children and babies</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-59_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Step-by-step first aid treatment</strong></h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-btwLGw cuLvxI pf-61_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-62_ pf-text-1"><strong>Keep calm</strong> - Comfort the child or baby, as crying can increase blood pressure, exacerbating the bleed.












</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-64_ pf-text-1"><strong>Positioning </strong>- Have the child sit up straight, and tilt their head slightly forward. Lying down or tilting the head back can cause blood to run down the throat.


















</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-66_ pf-text-1"><strong>Pinching the nose</strong> - Gently pinch the soft part of the nose (not the bone) between your thumb and finger. Hold it for ten minutes, and check if the bleeding has stopped.


















</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-68_ pf-text-1"><strong>Applying ice</strong> - Place a cold pack or wrapped ice on the bridge of the nose to help constrict the tiny blood vessels.



















</li></ul><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-70_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>What to avoid
